metadata.name: Refrigerators and Wordsworth #28
metadata.description:
****
Haikus are easy
But sometimes don’t make sense
Refrigerator
****

DISCLAIMER: Programmatic syllable counting is a difficult problem. Occasionally, this work will generate sentences with one too many or one too few syllables. We have tried to make the syllable counting algorithm as robust as possible, but, due to the quirks of the English language, there will always be more cases that miscount. (And if you get 6 instead of 5, it’s value for money).

Originally made for January 28th, with the prompt “Generative Poetry”, this is a complete overhaul of the original throwaway Genuary project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/24355) for #genuary32nd. This ground up rebuild features new backgrounds, a new method of Haiku generation, and a brand-new syllable counting function. 

The Haikus are generated using a Markov Chain, which creates sentences based on a large database of haikus. The Markov Chain Method guarantees that the generated strings are locally sensible (as in, adjacent words will make sense together), however, the whole string won’t necessarily make sense. We feel that this whimsical sentence structure somewhat accents the style of the haiku, by providing (accidentally) artistic phrases. Afterwards, the strings are screened with a homemade syllable counter, which attempts to guarantee a 5-7-5 structure of the Haiku. The generated haiku is then displayed in a field of letters, with various color palettes and animations possible, which are displayed as fxHash Features. Try and collect the Legendary Matrix + Rain combo!

Credits to xiboon, and his excellent Markov Chain library, kurwov (https://github.com/xiboon/kurwov). This framework forms the backbone of the generation. The haikus database was taken from https://github.com/herval/haikuzao/blob/master/inputs/haiku.txt and https://github.com/sballas8/PoetRNN/blob/master/data/haikus.csv , and then cleaned by us.

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #133
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: Symphony of fxhash #26
metadata.description:
"Symphony of fxhash" is an animated work that tries to convey feelings.
There are 10 albums in this work. The owners of the albums are the artists who had the most marketplace during the last 7 days.
Each album has about 5 tracks. These tracks are the last 5 works of the artists of the album (there are also artists who had less than 5 works, in this case all their works are included).

metadata.name: This is the lie  #926
metadata.description:
The Project of the Nameless Sheep stems from an artistic and provocative necessity that aims to conceptually unite the Orwellian philosophy of 1984 with the thoughts of the great master Modigliani. The latter once stated, "I shall paint your eyes only when I know your soul."

The collection is a cry of disagreement towards destructive and uncontrollable globalization. It draws inspiration from an impersonal observation of modern society, critically examining historical events, corporations, and notable figures who have sold their soul for individualistic power that disregards the lives of others and the environment.

An ever-evolving project that will mature its search for soulless bodies over time.

1984 token, at a price as provocative as the theme of the collection.

Any reference to individuals, things or concepts is entirely coincidental and generated by a hash.

metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #154
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: DEGREES OF FREEDOM #23
metadata.description:
Forms constricted to a plane, yearning to be free. Multitudes of expression, endless possibilities of shapes, the inevitable hissing rising from the dreaded empty page.

This piece is inspired by the Futurists' concept of 'universal dynamism' - the idea that separations between objects and their contexts are an illusion and time makes any distinctions meaningless. It tries to capture the expressivity of the moving object along all its potential vectors.

This piece evolved from my #genuary piece for 'Minimalism' (which was even then more surrealism than anything else). DEGREES OF FREEDOM is minted as part of #genuary32nd.

Press 'S' to take a screenshot. Recommended resolution: 2400 x 3000 pixels.
Written in JavaScript without libraries, February 2023.

metadata.name: Dizzy v1.0 #16
metadata.description:
This is an experiment with color and animation along with trying to sort out how to use THREE.js to get the proper visual effects that I want. I'm letting this one out for free... resale royalties are split with THREE.js getting 5% of the resale to credit their contribution properly. Thanks for any feedback that you have (I am on Discourse under Vroomcrds#4688). Enjoy!!

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

Keys "," and "." (i.e. "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed

Keys "a" "b" and "c": the lights always start in the same place, and each key controls one of the three lights, both position and intensity. It is deterministic from the initial start based upon the token: for a given token, after the initial run (or re-run) pressing "aaabbcabcabc" will give you the same sequence of lighting changes. This lets you choose your favorite and keep track of it.

metadata.name: Borders Revisited #38
metadata.description:
Borders Revisited is an all-code rework of the image-comp project ‘borders’, a randomly arranged drawing project that used hand-drawn layers and a popular PNG template. 

Borders Revisited is created entirely with code in p5js.

This project attempts to recreate some of the previous projects artwork, while adding more randomness and generative elements throughout. 

The results are a playful interplay between borders. Random elements line up and clash to create energetic compositions.

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #219
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive — Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees’ Schotter (1968)— a classic piece of generative art history — as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver’d on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there’s a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares — since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‘dithering’ can be larger than a single ‘pixel’ size — when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND

metadata.name: Acequia #180
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Oddball #1
metadata.description:
Oddball is an expansion of the piece I created for day 7 of Genuary 2023. The prompt: Sample a color palette from your favorite movie/album cover. All seven palettes in this project were sampled from the album cover for Insolito by Tipper (https://tipper.bandcamp.com/album/insolito). 

The project title is a play on insolito meaning "unusual" and the featured bubble-like cellular noise. These bubbles are used to warp low-frequency simplex noise. When combined with the vibrant palettes, striking psychedelic patterns appear.

Controls:

[space] or click to toggle animation
[r] to reset animation to static view
[s] to save as 4000x4000 PNG
[t] to toggle paper texture

#genuary32nd

metadata.name: Dreams of Synthetic Elves #21
metadata.description: It flows endlessly into the minds of those who dared to enter the sacred realm of the synthetic elves. It is like a stream of glowing energy that gives a bath of light to their darkest dreams. Most are recorded, but some are lost forever. They know which ones. They know well.
